> Can you provide a good example of affine types and how they help with expressiveness?<p>For example, let&#x27;s say there&#x27;s an HTTP server handler that must send each header line first, and finally send a body. So you should:<p><pre><code>  conn.send_header(&quot;HTTP/1.1 200 OK&quot;);
  conn.send_header(&quot;Connection: Close&quot;);
  conn.send_header(&quot;Content-type: text/html&quot;);
  conn.send_body(&quot;Hello, world!&quot;);
</code></pre>
In Rust, you can construct the API so that you <i>cannot</i> call `send_body` before any occurrences of `send_header`. So if you do:<p><pre><code>  conn.send_body(&quot;I&#x27;m sent first!&quot;);
  conn.send_header(&quot;Content-type: text/html&quot;);
</code></pre>
you will get a <i>compile error</i>. This greatly reduces the risk of having incorrect logic in your program. In this case Rust helps ensuring our intention: `send_body` can only be the last call of the request handler. I consider this a good example of expressiveness of Rust (and affine types).
